We will construct a "compatible system" of affine open covers of the X_n. It will be relevant, for this construction, to consider an open cover of a space Y as a diagram Y \xleftarrow {u} U \xrightarrow {\varphi } I where I is discrete, u is surjective, and u_i\colon U_i\coloneqq \varphi ^{-1}(i)\hookrightarrow Y is an open embedding. Proceeding as in , we construct a diagram
363hodge-theory-iii-9.3.3.1hodge-theory-iii-9.3.3.1.xmlEquation9.3.3.1hodge-theory-iii-9.3.3 X_\bullet \xleftarrow {u} U_\bullet \xrightarrow {\varphi } I_\bullet \tag{9.3.3.1}
of the following type.
I_\bullet is a discrete simplicial set. The I_n are finite.
For all k\geqslant 0, induces a diagram
\usepackage {amsmath} \usepackage {amssymb} \usepackage {tikz-cd} \begin {tikzcd} (\operatorname {cosq}\operatorname {sq}_{k-1}(X_\bullet ))_k & (\operatorname {cosq}\operatorname {sq}_{k-1}(U_\bullet ))_k \ar [l] \ar [r,"\varphi "] & (\operatorname {cosq}\operatorname {sq}_{k-1}(I_\bullet ))_k \\N_k \ar [u,"f'_k"] & N_k(U_\bullet ) \ar [u] \ar [l] \ar [r,swap,"\varphi "] & N_k(I_\bullet ) \ar [u,swap,"a'_k"] \end {tikzcd}
In the diagram in (b), for i\in \operatorname {cosq}\operatorname {sq}_{k-1}(I_\bullet )_k, the \varphi ^{-1}(j) for a'_k(j)=i form an affine open cover of N_k\times _{(\operatorname {cosq}\operatorname {sq}_{k-1}(X_\bullet ))_k} \varphi ^{-1}(i).
(Follows by induction on (c)). The first (and thus the second) row of the diagram in (b) defines an open cover. The X_k\leftarrow U_k\to I_k thus also form open covers.
(Follows from a suitable choice of affine covers in (c)). U_{n_i}=\varphi _n^{-1}(i) is the complement of a subscheme D_{n,i} of X_n, given by the union of a divisor and some connected components of X_n. For every coherent sheaf \mathscr {F} on X_n and integers (a_i)_{i\in I_n} (with (a_i\geqslant 0)), we set \mathscr {F}(\textstyle \sum _i a_i D_{n,i}) = \begin {cases} 0 &\text {on the components of }X_n\text { contained inside some }D_{n,i}\text { with }a_i>0 \\\mathscr {F}\otimes \mathcal {O}(\sum _{a_i>0}a_i D_{n,i}) &\text { on the others}. \end {cases}

We now prove that K satisfies .
    Properties (a) and (b) of K are clear;
    we define f\colon \Omega _X^\bullet \to  K by the evident maps from the \Omega _X^q to the K^{0,0,q}.

In the analytic category, the complex K^\mathrm {an} of coherent analytic sheaves is given by the same formulas as for K.
    We have a commutative diagram


    \usepackage {amsmath}
    \usepackage {amssymb}
    \usepackage {tikz-cd}
  \begin {tikzcd}
      \operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^i(X,K)
        \ar [r,"\sim "]
        \ar [d]
      & \operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^i(X_\bullet ,\Omega _{X_\bullet }^\bullet )
        \ar [d,"(1)"]
    \\\operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^i(X^\mathrm {an},K^\mathrm {an})
        \ar [r,"\sim "]
      & \operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^i(X_\bullet ^\mathrm {an},\Omega _{X_\bullet ^\mathrm {an}}^\bullet )
    \end {tikzcd}

    and (1) is an abutment of a morphism of spectral sequences


    \usepackage {amsmath}
    \usepackage {amssymb}
    \usepackage {tikz-cd}
  \begin {tikzcd}
      \operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^a(X_b,\Omega _{X_\bullet }^\bullet )
        \ar [r,Rightarrow]
        \ar [d]
      & \operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^{a+b}(X_\bullet ,\Omega _{X_\bullet }^\bullet )
        \ar [d]
    \\\operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^a(X_b^\mathrm {an},\Omega _{X_\bullet ^\mathrm {an}}^\bullet )
        \ar [r,Rightarrow]
      & \operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^{a+b}(X_\bullet ^\mathrm {an},\Omega _{X_\bullet ^\mathrm {an}}^\bullet ).
    \end {tikzcd}

    This morphism is an isomorphism by [G1966], whence (d).

